# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flac-lossless
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In digital audio using pulse-code modulation (PCM), **bit depth** is the number of bits of information in each sample, and it directly corresponds to the **resolution** of each sample.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Examples of bit depth include CD-DA and DVD-Video, which uses 16 bits per sample, and DVD-Audio and Blu-ray Disc, which can support up to 24 bits per sample.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In basic implementations, variations in bit depth primarily affect the noise level from quantization error—thus the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and dynamic range.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] However, techniques such as dithering, noise shaping, and oversampling can mitigate these effects without changing the bit depth.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bit depth also affects bit rate and file size.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bit depth is useful for describing PCM digital signals.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Non-PCM formats, such as those using lossy compression, do not have associated bit depths.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] A PCM signal is a sequence of digital audio samples containing the data providing the necessary information to reconstruct the original analog signal.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Each sample represents the amplitude of the signal at a specific point in time, and the samples are uniformly spaced in time.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The amplitude is the only information explicitly stored in the sample, and it is typically stored as either an integer or a floating-point number, encoded as a binary number with a fixed number of digits – the sample's *bit depth*, also referred to as word length or word size.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The resolution indicates the number of discrete values that can be represented over the range of analog values.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The resolution of binary integers increases exponentially as the word length increases: adding one bit doubles the resolution, adding two quadruples it, and so on.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The number of possible values that an integer bit depth can represent can be calculated by using 2*n*, where *n* is the bit depth.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Thus, a 16-bit system has a resolution of 65,536 (216) possible values.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Integer PCM audio data is typically stored as signed numbers in two's complement format.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Today, most audio file formats and digital audio workstations (DAWs) also support PCM formats with samples represented by floating-point numbers.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Both the WAV file format and the AIFF file format support floating-point representations.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Unlike integers, whose bit pattern is a single series of bits, a floating-point number is instead composed of separate fields whose mathematical relation forms a number.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The most common standard is IEEE 754, which is composed of three fields: a sign bit representing whether the number is positive or negative, a mantissa, and an exponent determining a power-of-two factor to scale the mantissa.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The mantissa is expressed as a binary fraction in IEEE base-two floating-point formats.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The bit depth limits the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of the reconstructed signal to a maximum level determined by quantization error.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The bit depth has no impact on the frequency response, which is constrained by the sample rate.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Quantization error introduced during analog-to-digital conversion (ADC) can be modeled as quantization noise.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The noise is nonlinear and signal-dependent.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] where *b* is the number of quantization bits, and the result is measured in decibels (dB).
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Therefore, 16-bit digital audio found on CDs has a theoretical maximum SNR of 98 dB, and professional 24-bit digital audio tops out as 146 dB.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] As of 2011, digital audio converter technology is limited to an SNR of about 123 dB (effectively 21 bits) because of real-world limitations in integrated circuit design.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Still, this approximately matches the performance of the human auditory system.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Multiple converters can be used to cover different ranges of the same signal, being combined to record a wider dynamic range in the long-term, while still being limited by the single converter's dynamic range in the short term, which is called *dynamic range extension*.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The resolution of floating-point samples is less straightforward than integer samples because floating-point values are not evenly spaced.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In floating-point representation, the space between any two adjacent values is in proportion to the value.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The trade-off between floating-point and integer formats is that the space between large floating-point values is greater than the space between large integer values of the same bit depth.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Rounding a large floating-point number results in a greater error than rounding a small floating-point number whereas rounding an integer number will always result in the same level of error.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In other words, integers have a round-off that is uniform, always rounding the LSB to 0 or 1, and the floating-point format has uniform SNR, the quantization noise level is always of a certain proportion to the signal level.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] A floating-point noise floor rises as the signal rises and falls as the signal falls, resulting in audible variance if the bit depth is low enough.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Most processing operations on digital audio involve the re-quantization of samples and thus introduce additional rounding errors analogous to the original quantization error introduced during analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] To prevent rounding errors larger than the implicit error during ADC, calculations during processing must be performed at higher precisions than the input samples.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Digital signal processing (DSP) operations can be performed in either fixed-point or floating-point precision.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In either case, the precision of each operation is determined by the precision of the hardware operations used to perform each step of the processing and not the resolution of the input data.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For example, on x86 processors, floating-point operations are performed with single or double precision, and fixed-point operations at 16-, 32- or 64-bit resolution.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Consequently, all processing performed on Intel-based hardware will be performed with these constraints regardless of the source format.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Fixed-point digital signal processors often supports specific word lengths to support specific signal resolutions.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For example, the Motorola 56000 DSP chip uses 24-bit multipliers and 56-bit accumulators to perform multiply-accumulate operations on two 24-bit samples without overflow or truncation.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] On devices that do not support large accumulators, fixed-point results may be truncated, reducing precision.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Errors compound through multiple stages of DSP at a rate that depends on the operations being performed.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For uncorrelated processing steps on audio data without a DC offset, errors are assumed to be random with zero means.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Under this assumption, the standard deviation of the distribution represents the error signal, and quantization error scales with the square root of the number of operations.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] High levels of precision are necessary for algorithms that involve repeated processing, such as convolution.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] High levels of precision are also necessary in recursive algorithms, such as infinite impulse response (IIR) filters.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In the particular case of IIR filters, rounding error can degrade frequency response and cause instability.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The noise introduced by quantization error, including rounding errors and loss of precision introduced during audio processing, can be mitigated by adding a small amount of random noise, called dither, to the signal before quantizing.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Dithering eliminates non-linear quantization error behavior, giving very low distortion, but at the expense of a slightly raised noise floor.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Recommended dither for 16-bit digital audio measured using ITU-R 468 noise weighting is about 66 dB below alignment level, or 84 dB below digital full scale, which is comparable to the microphone and room noise level, and hence of little consequence in 16-bit audio.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] 24-bit and 32-bit audio does not require dithering, as the noise level of the digital converter is always louder than the required level of any dither that might be applied.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] 24-bit audio could theoretically encode 144 dB of dynamic range, and 32-bit audio can achieve 192 dB, but this is almost impossible to achieve in the real world, as even the best sensors and microphones rarely exceed 130 dB.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Dither can also be used to increase the effective dynamic range.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The *perceived* dynamic range of 16-bit audio can be 120 dB or more with noise-shaped dither, taking advantage of the frequency response of the human ear.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Dynamic range is the difference between the largest and smallest signal a system can record or reproduce.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Without dither, the dynamic range correlates to the quantization noise floor.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For example, 16-bit integer resolution allows for a dynamic range of about 96 dB.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] With the proper application of dither, digital systems can reproduce signals with levels lower than their resolution would normally allow, extending the effective dynamic range beyond the limit imposed by the resolution.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The use of techniques such as oversampling and noise shaping can further extend the dynamic range of sampled audio by moving quantization error out of the frequency band of interest.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] If the signal's maximum level is lower than that allowed by the bit depth, the recording has headroom.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Using higher bit depths during studio recording can make headroom available while maintaining the same dynamic range.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] This reduces the risk of clipping without increasing quantization errors at low volumes.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Oversampling is an alternative method to increase the dynamic range of PCM audio without changing the number of bits per sample.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In oversampling, audio samples are acquired at a multiple of the desired sample rate.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Because quantization error is assumed to be uniformly distributed with frequency, much of the quantization error is shifted to ultrasonic frequencies and can be removed by the digital-to-analog converter during playback.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For example, a 14-bit ADC can produce 16-bit 48 kHz audio if operated at 16× oversampling, or 768 kHz.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Oversampled PCM, therefore, exchanges fewer bits per sample for more samples to obtain the same resolution.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Dynamic range can also be enhanced with oversampling at signal reconstruction, absent oversampling at the source.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Consider 16× oversampling at reconstruction.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Each sample at reconstruction would be unique in that for each of the original sample points, sixteen are inserted, all having been calculated by a digital reconstruction filter.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The mechanism of increased effective bit depth is as previously discussed, that is, quantization noise power has not been reduced, but the noise spectrum has been spread over 16× the audio bandwidth.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Historical note—The compact disc standard was developed by a collaboration between Sony and Philips.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] The first Sony consumer unit featured a 16-bit DAC; the first Philips units had dual 14-bit DACs.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] This confused the marketplace and even in professional circles, because 14-bit PCM allows for 84 dB SNR, 12 dB less than 16-bit PCM.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Philips had implemented 4× oversampling with first order noise shaping which theoretically realized the full 96 dB dynamic range of the CD format.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In practice the Philips CD100 was rated at 90 dB SNR in the audio band of 20 Hz–20 kHz, the same as Sony's CDP-101.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Oversampling a signal results in equal quantization noise per unit of bandwidth at all frequencies and a dynamic range that improves with only the square root of the oversampling ratio.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Noise shaping is a technique that adds additional noise at higher frequencies, which cancels out some error at lower frequencies, resulting in a larger increase in dynamic range when oversampling.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For *n*th-order noise shaping, the dynamic range of an oversampled signal is improved by an additional 6*n* dB relative to oversampling without noise shaping.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] For example, for a 20 kHz analog audio sampled at 4× oversampling with second-order noise shaping, the dynamic range is increased by 30 dB.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Therefore, a 16-bit signal sampled at 176 kHz would have a bit depth equal to a 21-bit signal sampled at 44.1 kHz without noise shaping.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Noise shaping is commonly implemented with delta-sigma modulation.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Using delta-sigma modulation, Direct Stream Digital achieves a theoretical 120 dB SNR at audio frequencies using 1-bit audio with 64× oversampling.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bit depth is a fundamental property of digital audio implementations.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Depending on application requirements and equipment capabilities, different bit depths are used for different applications.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Blu-ray supports a variety of non-LPCM formats but all conform to some combination of 16, 20, or 24 bits per sample.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] ITU-T specifies the A-law and μ-law companding algorithms, compressing down from 13 and 14 bits respectively.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] NICAM systems 1, 2 and 3 compress down from 13, 14 and 14 bits respectively.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bit depth affects bit rate and file size.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bits are the basic unit of data used in computing and digital communications.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] Bit rate refers to the amount of data, specifically bits, transmitted or received per second.
[src:flac-lossless/audio-bit-depth] In MP3 and other lossy compressed audio formats, bit rate describes the amount of information used to encode an audio signal.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC is an open format with royalty-free licensing and a reference implementation which is free software.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC supports metadata tagging, album cover art, and fast seeking.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Development was started in 2000 by Josh Coalson.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The bitstream format was frozen with the release of version 0.9 of the reference implementation on 31 March 2001.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Version 1.0 was released on 20 July 2001.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] On 29 January 2003, the Xiph.Org Foundation and the FLAC project announced the incorporation of FLAC under the Xiph.org banner.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Xiph.org is home to other free compression formats such as Vorbis, Theora, Speex and Opus.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Version 1.3.0 was released on 26 May 2013, at which point development was moved to the Xiph.org git repository.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] In 2019, FLAC was proposed as an IETF standard.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] In December 2024, FLAC was formally specified in and published as RFC 9639.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC is a lossless encoding of linear pulse-code modulation data.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] A FLAC file consists of the magic number `fLaC`, metadata, and encoded audio.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The encoded audio is divided into frames, each of which consists of a header, a data block, and a CRC16 checksum.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Each frame is encoded independently of the others.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] A frame header begins with a sync word, used to identify the beginning of a valid frame.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The rest of the header contains the number of samples, position of the frame, channel assignment, and optionally the sample rate and bit depth.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The data block contains the audio information.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Properties like the sample rate and the number of channels are always contained in the metadata.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] It may also contain other information, the album cover, for example.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC uses Vorbis comments for textual metadata like track title and artist name.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The FLAC encoding algorithm consists of multiple stages.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] In the first stage, the input audio is split into blocks.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] If the audio contains multiple channels, each channel is encoded separately as a subblock.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The encoder then tries to find a good mathematical approximation of the block, either by fitting a simple polynomial, or through general linear predictive coding.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] A description of the approximation, which is only a few bytes in length, is then written.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Finally, the difference between the approximation and the input, called residual, is encoded using Rice coding.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] In many cases, a description of the approximation and the encoded residual takes up less space than using pulse-code modulation.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The decoding process is the reverse of encoding.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The compressed residual is first decoded.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The description of the mathematical approximation is then used to calculate a waveform.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The result is formed by adding the residual and the calculated waveform.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] As FLAC compresses losslessly, the decoded waveform is identical to the waveform before encoding.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] For two-channel stereo, the encoder may choose to joint-encode the audio.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The channels are transformed into a side channel, which is the difference between the two input channels, and a mid channel, the sum of the two input channels.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] In place of a mid channel, the left channel or the right channel may be encoded instead, which is sometimes more space-efficient.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Even though the reference encoder uses a single block size for the whole stream, FLAC allows the block size in samples to vary per block.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The amount of compression is determined by various parameters, including the order of the linear prediction model and the block size.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Regardless of the amount of compression, the original data can always be reconstructed perfectly.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] For the user's convenience, the reference implementation defines 9 compression levels, which are presets of the more technical parameters to the encoding algorithm.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The levels are labeled from 0 to 8, with higher numbers resulting in a higher compression ratio, at the cost of compression speed.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The meaning of each compression level varies by implementation.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC is optimized for decoding speed at the expense of encoding speed.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] A benchmark has shown that, while there is little variation in decoding speed as compression level increases, beyond the default compression level 5, the encoding process takes up considerably more time with little space saved compared to level 5.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The FLAC format, along with libFLAC, is not known to be covered by any patents, and anyone is free to write their own implementations of FLAC.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC is specifically designed for efficient packing of audio data, unlike general-purpose lossless algorithms such as DEFLATE, which are used in ZIP and gzip.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] While ZIP may reduce the size of a CD-quality audio file by 10–20%, FLAC is able to reduce the size of audio data by 40–50% by taking advantage of the characteristics of audio.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The technical strengths of FLAC compared to other lossless formats lie in its ability to be streamed and decoded quickly, independent of compression level.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Since FLAC is a lossless scheme, it is suitable as an archive format for owners of CDs and other media who wish to preserve their audio collections.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] If the original media are lost, damaged, or worn out, a FLAC copy of the audio tracks ensures that an exact duplicate of the original data can be recovered at any time.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] An exact restoration from a lossy copy (e.g., MP3) of the same data is impossible.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC's being lossless means it is highly suitable for transcoding, e.g., to MP3, without the normally associated transcoding quality loss between one lossy format and another.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] A CUE file can optionally be created when ripping a CD.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] If a CD is read and ripped perfectly to FLAC files, the CUE file allows later burning of an audio CD that is identical in audio data to the original CD, including track order and pregap, but excluding additional data such as lyrics and CD+G graphics.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] But depending on the burning program used, CD-Text may be recovered from the metadata stored in the CUE sheet and burned back to a new copy on blank CD-R media.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The reference implementation of FLAC is implemented as the *libFLAC* core encoder & decoder library, with the main distributable program `flac` being the reference implementation of the libFLAC API.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] This codec API is also available in C++ as libFLAC++.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The reference implementation of FLAC compiles on many platforms, including most Unix (such as Solaris, BSD) and Unix-like (including Linux), Windows, BeOS, and OS/2 operating systems.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] There are build systems for autotools and CMake.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] There is currently no multicore support in libFLAC, but utilities such as GNU parallel and various graphical frontends can be used to spin up multiple instances of the encoder.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC playback support in portable audio devices and dedicated audio systems is limited compared to formats such as MP3 or uncompressed PCM.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] FLAC support is included by default in Windows 10, Android, macOS and iOS.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] Various other containers are supported, independently of the operating system used, depending on the playback software used.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The standardization process of the FLAC format into RFC 9639 was driven by the specific use case of archival and preservation in mind.
[src:flac-lossless/flac] The National Archives and Records Administration of the United States has FLAC listed as a preferred format for digital audio.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC is the most widely used method in speech coding and speech synthesis.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] It is a powerful speech analysis technique, and a useful method for encoding good quality speech at a low bit rate.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC starts with the assumption that a speech signal is produced by a buzzer at the end of a tube (for voiced sounds), with occasional added hissing and popping sounds (for voiceless sounds such as sibilants and plosives).
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Although apparently crude, this Source–filter model is actually a close approximation of the reality of speech production.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] The glottis (the space between the vocal folds) produces the buzz, which is characterized by its intensity (loudness) and frequency (pitch).
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] The vocal tract (the throat and mouth) forms the tube, which is characterized by its resonances; these resonances give rise to formants, or enhanced frequency bands in the sound produced.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Hisses and pops are generated by the action of the tongue, lips and throat during sibilants and plosives.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC analyzes the speech signal by estimating the formants, removing their effects from the speech signal, and estimating the intensity and frequency of the remaining buzz.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] The process of removing the formants is called inverse filtering, and the remaining signal after the subtraction of the filtered modeled signal is called the residue.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] The numbers which describe the intensity and frequency of the buzz, the formants, and the residue signal, can be stored or transmitted somewhere else.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC synthesizes the speech signal by reversing the process: use the buzz parameters and the residue to create a source signal, use the formants to create a filter (which represents the tube), and run the source through the filter, resulting in speech.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Because speech signals vary with time, this process is done on short chunks of the speech signal, which are called frames; generally, 30 to 50 frames per second give an intelligible speech with good compression.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Linear prediction (signal estimation) goes back to at least the 1940s when Norbert Wiener developed a mathematical theory for calculating the best filters and predictors for detecting signals hidden in noise.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Soon after Claude Shannon established a general theory of coding, work on predictive coding was done by C.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Peter Elias in 1955 published two papers on predictive coding of signals.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Linear predictors were applied to speech analysis independently by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone in 1966 and in 1967 by Bishnu S.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Itakura and Saito described a statistical approach based on maximum likelihood estimation; Atal and Schroeder described an adaptive linear predictor approach; Burg outlined an approach based on principle of maximum entropy.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1969, Itakura and Saito introduced a method based on partial correlation (PARCOR), Glen Culler proposed real-time speech encoding, and Bishnu S.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Atal presented an LPC speech coder at the Annual Meeting of the Acoustical Society of America.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1971, realtime LPC using 16-bit LPC hardware was demonstrated by Philco-Ford; four units were sold.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC technology was advanced by Bishnu Atal and Manfred Schroeder during the 1970s–1980s.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1978, Atal and Vishwanath *et al.* of BBN developed the first variable-rate LPC algorithm.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Schroeder at Bell Labs proposed an LPC speech codec called adaptive predictive coding, which used a psychoacoustic coding algorithm exploiting the masking properties of the human ear.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] This later became the basis for the perceptual coding technique used by the MP3 audio compression format, introduced in 1993.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Code-excited linear prediction (CELP) was developed by Schroeder and Atal in 1985.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC is the basis for voice-over-IP (VoIP) technology.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1972, Bob Kahn of ARPA with Jim Forgie of Lincoln Laboratory (LL) and Dave Walden of BBN Technologies started the first developments in packetized speech, which would eventually lead to voice-over-IP technology.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1973, according to Lincoln Laboratory informal history, the first real-time 2400 bit/s LPC was implemented by Ed Hofstetter.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In 1974, the first real-time two-way LPC packet speech communication was accomplished over the ARPANET at 3500 bit/s between Culler-Harrison and Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC is frequently used for transmitting spectral envelope information, and as such it has to be tolerant of transmission errors.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Transmission of the filter coefficients directly (see linear prediction for a definition of coefficients) is undesirable, since they are very sensitive to errors.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] In other words, a very small error can distort the whole spectrum, or worse, a small error might make the prediction filter unstable.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] There are more advanced representations such as log area ratios (LAR), line spectral pairs (LSP) decomposition and reflection coefficients.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Of these, especially LSP decomposition has gained popularity since it ensures the stability of the predictor, and spectral errors are local for small coefficient deviations.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] It is generally used for speech analysis and resynthesis.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] It is used as a form of voice compression by phone companies, such as in the GSM standard, for example.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] It is also used for secure wireless, where voice must be digitized, encrypted and sent over a narrow voice channel; an early example of this is the US government's Navajo I.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC synthesis can be used to construct vocoders where musical instruments are used as an excitation signal to the time-varying filter estimated from a singer's speech.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] This is somewhat popular in electronic music.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] Paul Lansky made the well-known computer music piece notjustmoreidlechatter using linear predictive coding.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] A 10th-order LPC was used in the popular 1980s Speak & Spell educational toy.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC predictors are used in Shorten, MPEG-4 ALS, FLAC, SILK audio codec, and other lossless audio codecs.
[src:flac-lossless/linear-predictive-coding] LPC has received some attention as a tool for use in the tonal analysis of violins and other stringed musical instruments.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] By operation of the pigeonhole principle, no lossless compression algorithm can shrink the size of all possible data: Some data will get longer by at least one symbol or bit.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Compression algorithms are usually effective for human- and machine-readable documents and cannot shrink the size of random data that contain no redundancy.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression is used in many applications.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For example, it is used in the ZIP file format and in the GNU tool gzip.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] It is also often used as a component within lossy data compression technologies (e.g. lossless mid/side joint stereo preprocessing by MP3 encoders and other lossy audio encoders).
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless compression is used in cases where it is important that the original and the decompressed data be identical, or where deviations from the original data would be unfavourable.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Common examples are executable programs, text documents, and source code.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Some image file formats, like PNG or GIF, use only lossless compression, while others like TIFF and MNG may use either lossless or lossy methods.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless audio formats are most often used for archiving or production purposes, while smaller lossy audio files are typically used on portable players and in other cases where storage space is limited or exact replication of the audio is unnecessary.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The primary encoding algorithms used to produce bit sequences are Huffman coding (also used by the deflate algorithm) and arithmetic coding.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Arithmetic coding achieves compression rates close to the best possible for a particular statistical model, which is given by the information entropy, whereas Huffman compression is simpler and faster but produces poor results for models that deal with symbol probabilities close to 1.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] There are two primary ways of constructing statistical models: in a *static* model, the data is analyzed and a model is constructed, then this model is stored with the compressed data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This approach is simple and modular, but has the disadvantage that the model itself can be expensive to store, and also that it forces using a single model for all data being compressed, and so performs poorly on files that contain heterogeneous data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] *Adaptive* models dynamically update the model as the data is compressed.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Both the encoder and decoder begin with a trivial model, yielding poor compression of initial data, but as they learn more about the data, performance improves.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Most popular types of compression used in practice now use adaptive coders.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless compression methods may be categorized according to the type of data they are designed to compress.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] While, in principle, any general-purpose lossless compression algorithm (*general-purpose* meaning that they can accept any bitstring) can be used on any type of data, many are unable to achieve significant compression on data that are not of the form for which they were designed to compress.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Many of the lossless compression techniques used for text also work reasonably well for indexed-color images.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] These techniques take advantage of the specific characteristics of images such as the common phenomenon of contiguous 2-D areas of similar tones.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Every pixel but the first is replaced by the difference to its left neighbor.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This leads to small values having a much higher probability than large values.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This is often also applied to sound files, and can compress files that contain mostly low frequencies and low volumes.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For images, this step can be repeated by taking the difference to the top pixel, and then in videos, the difference to the pixel in the next frame can be taken.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The adaptive encoding uses the probabilities from the previous sample in sound encoding, from the left and upper pixel in image encoding, and additionally from the previous frame in video encoding.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In the wavelet transformation, the probabilities are also passed through the hierarchy.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Many of these methods are implemented in open-source and proprietary tools, particularly LZW and its variants.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Some algorithms are patented in the United States and other countries and their legal usage requires licensing by the patent holder.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] However, the patents on LZW expired on June 20, 2003.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] As mentioned previously, lossless sound compression is a somewhat specialized area.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless sound compression algorithms can take advantage of the repeating patterns shown by the wave-like nature of the data‍—‍essentially using autoregressive models to predict the "next" value and encoding the (possibly small) difference between the expected value and the actual data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] If the difference between the predicted and the actual data (called the *error*) tends to be small, then certain difference values (like 0, +1, −1 etc. on sample values) become very frequent, which can be exploited by encoding them in few output bits.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] It is sometimes beneficial to compress only the differences between two versions of a file (or, in video compression, of successive images within a sequence).
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This is called delta encoding (from the Greek letter Δ, which in mathematics, denotes a difference), but the term is typically only used if both versions are meaningful outside compression and decompression.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For example, while the process of compressing the error in the above-mentioned lossless audio compression scheme could be described as delta encoding from the approximated sound wave to the original sound wave, the approximated version of the sound wave is not meaningful in any other context.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] No lossless compression algorithm can efficiently compress all possible data .
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For this reason, many different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Some of the most common lossless compression algorithms are listed below.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Cryptosystems often compress data (the "plaintext") *before* encryption for added security.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] When properly implemented, compression greatly increases the unicity distance by removing patterns that might facilitate cryptanalysis.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] However, many ordinary lossless compression algorithms produce headers, wrappers, tables, or other predictable output that might instead make cryptanalysis easier.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Thus, cryptosystems must utilize compression algorithms whose output does not contain these predictable patterns.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Genetics compression algorithms (not to be confused with genetic algorithms) are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and specific algorithms adapted to genetic data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published the first genetic compression algorithm that does not rely on external genetic databases for compression.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression much faster than leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Genomic sequence compression algorithms, also known as DNA sequence compressors, explore the fact that DNA sequences have characteristic properties, such as inverted repeats.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The most successful compressors are XM and GeCo.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For eukaryotes XM is slightly better in compression ratio, though for sequences larger than 100 MB its computational requirements are impractical.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Self-extracting executables contain a compressed application and a decompressor.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] When executed, the decompressor transparently decompresses and runs the original application.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This is especially often used in demo coding, where competitions are held for demos with strict size limits, as small as 1 kilobyte.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This type of compression is not strictly limited to binary executables, but can also be applied to scripts, such as JavaScript.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless compression algorithms and their implementations are routinely tested in head-to-head benchmarks.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] There are a number of better-known compression benchmarks.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Some benchmarks cover only the data compression ratio, so winners in these benchmarks may be unsuitable for everyday use due to the slow speed of the top performers.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Another drawback of some benchmarks is that their data files are known, so some program writers may optimize their programs for best performance on a particular data set.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The winners on these benchmarks often come from the class of context-mixing compression software.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The Compression Ratings website published a chart summary of the "frontier" in compression ratio and time.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The **Silesia corpus** is a collection of files that was created in 2003 as an alternative for the Canterbury corpus and Calgary corpus, based on concerns about how well these represented modern files.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] It contains various data types, including large text documents, executable files, and databases.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] It is widely used in data compression research.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The corpus consists of 12 files, totaling 211MB.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The files were chosen to represent what the author considered to be data types likely to grow rapidly in size over time, such as computer programs and databases, along with more traditional compression benchmarks, such as large text files.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Because it has a broader and more modern selection of datatypes, it is considered a better source of test data for compression algorithms when compared to the Calgary corpus.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms cannot guarantee compression for all input data sets.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In other words, for any lossless data compression algorithm, there will be an input data set that does not get smaller when processed by the algorithm, and for any lossless data compression algorithm that makes at least one file smaller, there will be at least one file that it makes larger.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Most practical compression algorithms provide an "escape" facility that can turn off the normal coding for files that would become longer by being encoded.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In theory, only a single additional bit is required to tell the decoder that the normal coding has been turned off for the entire input; however, most encoding algorithms use at least one full byte (and typically more than one) for this purpose.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For example, deflate compressed files never need to grow by more than 5 bytes per 65,535 bytes of input.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In fact, if we consider files of length N, if all files were equally probable, then for any lossless compression that reduces the size of some file, the expected length of a compressed file (averaged over all possible files of length N) must necessarily be *greater* than N.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] So if we know nothing about the properties of the data we are compressing, we might as well not compress it at all.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] A lossless compression algorithm is useful only when we are more likely to compress certain types of files than others; then the algorithm could be designed to compress those types of data better.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Thus, the main lesson from the argument is not that one risks big losses, but merely that one cannot always win.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] To choose an algorithm always means implicitly to select a *subset* of all files that will become usefully shorter.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] This is the theoretical reason why we need to have different compression algorithms for different kinds of files: there cannot be any algorithm that is good for all kinds of data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Algorithms are generally quite specifically tuned to a particular type of file: for example, lossless audio compression programs do not work well on text files, and vice versa.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] In particular, files of random data cannot be consistently compressed by any conceivable lossless data compression algorithm; indeed, this result is used to *define* the concept of randomness in Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] It is provably impossible to create an algorithm that can losslessly compress any data.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Such an algorithm contradicts fundamental laws of mathematics because, if it existed, it could be applied repeatedly to losslessly reduce any file to length 1.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] On the other hand, it has also been proven that there is no algorithm to determine whether a file is incompressible in the sense of Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Hence it is possible that any particular file, even if it appears random, may be significantly compressed, even including the size of the decompressor.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] An example is the digits of the mathematical constant *pi*, which appear random but can be generated by a very small program.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] However, even though it cannot be determined whether a particular file is incompressible, a simple theorem about incompressible strings shows that over 99% of files of any given length cannot be compressed by more than one byte (including the size of the decompressor).
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Abstractly, a compression algorithm can be viewed as a function on sequences (normally of octets).
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Compression is successful if the resulting sequence is shorter than the original sequence (and the instructions for the decompression map).
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For a compression algorithm to be lossless, the compression map must form an injection from "plain" to "compressed" bit sequences.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] The pigeonhole principle prohibits a bijection between the collection of sequences of length *N* and any subset of the collection of sequences of length *N*−1.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Therefore, it is not possible to produce a lossless algorithm that reduces the size of every possible input sequence.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Real compression algorithm designers accept that streams of high information entropy cannot be compressed, and accordingly, include facilities for detecting and handling this condition.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] An obvious way of detection is applying a raw compression algorithm and testing if its output is smaller than its input.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] Sometimes, detection is made by heuristics; for example, a compression application may consider files whose names end in ".zip", ".arj" or ".lha" uncompressible without any more sophisticated detection.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] A common way of handling this situation is quoting input, or uncompressible parts of the input in the output, minimizing the compression overhead.
[src:flac-lossless/lossless-compression] For example, the zip data format specifies the 'compression method' of 'Stored' for input files that have been copied into the archive verbatim.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Rice was motivated to propose this simpler subset due to the fact that geometric distributions are often varying with time, not precisely known, or both, so selecting the seemingly optimal code might not be very advantageous.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Rice coding is used as the entropy encoding stage in a number of lossless image compression and audio data compression methods.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Golomb coding uses a tunable parameter M to divide an input value x into two parts: q, the result of a division by M, and r, the remainder.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The quotient is sent in unary coding, followed by the remainder in truncated binary encoding.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] When $M=1$ , Golomb coding is equivalent to unary coding.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Golomb–Rice codes can be thought of as codes that indicate a number by the position of the *bin* (q), and the *offset* within the *bin* (r).
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The example figure shows the position q and offset r for the encoding of integer x using Golomb–Rice parameter *M* = 3, with source probabilities following a geometric distribution with *p*(0) = 0.2.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Both q and r will be encoded using variable numbers of bits: q by a unary code, and r by b bits for Rice code, or a choice between b and *b*+1 bits for Golomb code (i.e.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] M is not a power of 2), with $b=\lfloor \log _{2}(M)\rfloor$ .
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] If $r<2^{b+1}-M$ , then use b bits to encode r; otherwise, use b+1 bits to encode r.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Clearly, $b=\log _{2}(M)$ if M is a power of 2 and we can encode all values of r with b bits.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The integer x treated by Golomb was the run length of a Bernoulli process, which has a geometric distribution starting at 0.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The best choice of parameter M is a function of the corresponding Bernoulli process, which is parameterized by $p=P(x=0)$ the probability of success in a given Bernoulli trial.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] M is either the median of the distribution or the median ±1.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The Golomb code for this distribution is equivalent to the Huffman code for the same probabilities, if it were possible to compute the Huffman code for the infinite set of source values.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Golomb's scheme was designed to encode sequences of non-negative numbers.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] However, it is easily extended to accept sequences containing negative numbers using an *overlap and interleave* scheme, in which all values are reassigned to some positive number in a unique and reversible way.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The *n*-th negative value (i.e., ⁠ $-n$ ⁠) is mapped to the *n*th odd number (⁠ $2n-1$ ⁠), and the *m*th positive value is mapped to the *m*-th even number (⁠ $2m$ ⁠).
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] This may be expressed mathematically as follows: a positive value x is mapped to ( $x'=2|x|=2x,\ x\geq 0$ ), and a negative value y is mapped to ( $y'=2|y|-1=-2y-1,\ y<0$ ).
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Such a code may be used for simplicity, even if suboptimal.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Truly optimal codes for two-sided geometric distributions include multiple variants of the Golomb code, depending on the distribution parameters, including this one.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] If $r\geq 2^{b+1}-M$ code the number $r+2^{b+1}-M$ in binary representation using *b* + 1 bits.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] are reversed in this section compared to the use in earlier sections.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Given an alphabet of two symbols, or a set of two events, *P* and *Q*, with probabilities *p* and (1 − *p*) respectively, where *p* ≥ 1/2, Golomb coding can be used to encode runs of zero or more *P*′s separated by single *Q*′s.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] In this application, the best setting of the parameter *M* is the nearest integer to $-{\frac {1}{\log _{2}p}}$ .
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] When *p* = 1/2, *M* = 1, and the Golomb code corresponds to unary (*n* ≥ 0 *P*′s followed by a *Q* is encoded as *n* ones followed by a zero).
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] (Rice himself proposed using various codes for the same data to figure out which was best.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Consider using a Rice code with a binary portion having b bits to run-length encode sequences where *P* has a probability p.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Compression is often expressed in terms of $1-\mathbb {E} [{\text{compression ratio}}]$ , the proportion compressed.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] For $p\approx 1$ , the run-length coding approach results in compression ratios close to entropy.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] For example, using Rice code $b=6$ for $p=0.99$ yields 91.89% compression, while the entropy limit is 91.92%.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] When a probability distribution for integers is not known, the optimal parameter for a Golomb–Rice encoder cannot be determined.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Thus, in many applications, a two-pass approach is used: first, the block of data is scanned to estimate a probability density function (PDF) for the data.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The Golomb–Rice parameter is then determined from that estimated PDF.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] A simpler variation of that approach is to assume that the PDF belongs to a parametrized family, estimate the PDF parameters from the data, and then compute the optimal Golomb–Rice parameter.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] That is the approach used in most of the applications discussed below.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] An alternative approach to efficiently encode integer data whose PDF is not known, or is varying, is to use a backwards-adaptive encoder.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The RLGR encoder [1] achieves that using a very simple algorithm that adjusts the Golomb–Rice parameter up or down, depending on the last encoded symbol.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] A decoder can follow the same rule to track the variation of the encoding parameters, so no side information needs to be transmitted, just the encoded data.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Assuming a generalized Gaussian PDF, which covers a wide range of statistics seen in data such as prediction errors or transform coefficients in multimedia codecs, the RLGR encoding algorithm can perform very well in such applications.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Numerous signal codecs use a Rice code for prediction residues.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] In predictive algorithms, such residues tend to fall into a two-sided geometric distribution, with small residues being more frequent than large residues, and the Rice code closely approximates the Huffman code for such a distribution without the overhead of having to transmit the Huffman table.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Several lossless audio codecs, such as Shorten, FLAC, Apple Lossless, and MPEG-4 ALS, use a Rice code after the linear prediction step (called "adaptive FIR filter" in Apple Lossless).
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] Rice coding is also used in the FELICS lossless image codec.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The Golomb–Rice coder is used in the entropy coding stage of Rice algorithm based *lossless image codecs*.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] One such experiment yields the compression ratio graph shown.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The JPEG-LS scheme uses Rice–Golomb to encode the prediction residuals.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] The RLGR adaptive version of Golomb–Rice coding mentioned above [2] is used for encoding screen content in virtual machines in the RemoteFX component of the Microsoft Remote Desktop Protocol.
[src:flac-lossless/rice-coding] It is also used in the recent G-PCC MPEG standard ISO/IEC 23090‑9 for point-cloud attribute compression.
